Angels Explained By Children

I only know the names of 
two angels, Hark and Harold.
Gregory, age 5

Everybody's got it all wrong. Angels 
don't wear halos anymore.Ā 
forget why,Ābut scientists 
are working on it 

-Olive, age 9

It's not easy to become an angel! 
First, you die.ĀThen you go to 
Heaven, and then there's 
still the flight training to go 
through. And then you 
got to agree to wear 
those angel clothes.
-Matthew, age 9 

Angels work for God and watch 
over kids when GodĀhas 
to go do something else. 
-Mitchell, age 7 

My guardian angel helps me 
with math, but he's 
not much good for science. 
-Henry, age 8

Angels don't eat, but they drink 
milk from HolyĀCows!!!Ā
-Jack, age 6

Angels talk all the way while 
they're flying you upĀ
to heaven. The main subject is 
where you went wrong 
before you got dead. 
Daniel, age 9Ā
Ā
When an angel gets mad, he takes 
a deep breath and counts to ten. 
And when he lets out his breath 
again,Ā somewhere there's a tornado. 
-Reagan, age 10

Angels have a lot to do and they keep 
very busy.ĀIf you lose a tooth, 
an angel comes in through 
your window and leaves money 
under your pillow. Then 
when it gets cold, angels go 
south for the winter.
Ā-Sara, age 6

Angels live in cloud houses made 
by God and hisĀson, 
who's a very good carpenter. 
-Jared, age 8 

All angels are girls because they 
gotta wearĀdresses 
and boys didn't go for it. 
-Antonio, age 9 
Ā
My angel is my grandma who died 
last year. She gotĀa big head start 
on helping me while she 
was still down here on earth. 
-Ashley ~ age 9 

Some of the angels are in charge of 
helping healĀsick animals and pets. 
And ifĀthey don't make the 
animals get better, they help 
the child get over it. 
-Vicki, age 8

What I don't get about angels is 
why, when someoneĀis in love, 
they shoot arrows at them. 




Ā 


